data.title: Alternating Currents announces first wave of music lineup for 2024 Quad-Cities festival
data.meta_description: Quad-Cities Arts festival Alternating Currents has announced the first set of performers on their lineup for August.
data.text:
Alternating Currents has announced part of its music lineup for 2024.

The annual arts festival will be held August 15 through August 18, at more than two dozen venues across the Quad-Cities. The event was founded by the Downtown Davenport Partnership, and has since expanded to include the Downtown Bettendorf Organization and Rock Island Downtown Alliance.

The festival is calling this wave of artists their "first drop," with a few more musicians and the full schedule to be announced later.

Many acts on the lineup are local, including favorites like Running Man, Frozen Fructose Laundromat, Lewis Knudsen, Angela Meyer and Einstein's Sister.

Einstein's Sister is a power-pop band who first made waves in the '90s, and returned with a sort of reunion last year. Their music re-emerged after the vinyl resurgence of the 2010's, and their latest EP was mixed and mastered at the famous Abbey Road Studios in the U.K.

"I'm working on stuff that I did in my basement, and I'm looking out the window, and there's the famous crosswalk," Einstein's Sister member Kerry Tucker said in October.

Einstein's Sister also played one of the last shows at Rock Island Brewing Co., the iconic venue in The District that closed its doors in December. So did Running Man, a local supergroup led by vocalist Skip Greer, who also serves as the frontman for legendary punk band The Dead Kennedys.

Frozen Fructose Laundromat is sure to be another highlight. The name certainly grabs attention. The band's lead songwriter Kevin Paller said in January that he got the naming idea from a memory in his teenage years, where he drank a root beer float at a laundromat in East Moline.

Frozen Fructose Laundromat's sophomore album, "A Comma Date," released earlier this year.

The festival lineup is largely curated by Quad-Cities figures like Sean Moeller at Raccoon Motel, Ragged Records, Common Chord and Hive Event Consulting. That local focus is what sets Alternating Currents apart from other festivals of its size, said Alisha Espey, director of programs for the Downtown Davenport Partnership.

"Any city can have a festival of scale where they're bringing larger acts to their community, but this one's special because we really are cultivating our local creators and putting them next to national touring artists," she said. "You get that community feel."

In the past, Alternating Currents has brought touring stars to the Quad-Cities, often before they reached national acclaim. "Brick" hitmaker Ben Folds, Grammy Award-winner Julien Baker and country star Morgan Wade have performed at the festival in the past.

"It's about discovery, so even if you don't necessarily recognize someone on the lineup today, that's the point," Espey said. "This is the opportunity to see rising stars."

This year, there are a few touring standouts.

Listen now and subscribe: Apple Podcasts | Google Podcasts | Spotify | RSS Feed | SoundStack

Nashville-based folk band The Mourning Doves are led by Paul McDonald, a singer-songwriter who once finished in the top 10 on "American Idol." As a solo artist, McDonald's performance of "All I've Ever Needed" has amassed millions of Spotify streams as part of "The Twilight Saga: Breaking Dawn - Part 2" soundtrack.

With their jazzy, brass-driven pop instrumentals, spunky Boston-based indie band Bermuda Search Party will be a hit for those who enjoy artists like Two Door Cinema Club and COIN.

Kansas power-pop group Ultimate Fakebook, which has been around since 1996, will resonate for fans of bands like Motion City Soundtrack and The Get Up Kids, both of which Ultimate Fakebook has toured with in the past.

Alternating Currents alumni Post Sex Nachos, Jaik Willis, Diplomats of Solid Sound, OTNES and Hembree will also be coming back.

Espey said that, this year, she's hoping to convey to attendees that Alternating Currents is not just a festival for niche music fans. She encourages everyone to use it as a chance to support local businesses, too. Since it started, the list of participating venues has doubled, Espey said.

"It's a festival of discovery, not just about artists, but about places," she said. "You can pick your favorite downtown restaurants and kind of camp there for the weekend if you want, and bounce back and forth, or make it a food crawl.

"The idea is just to come downtown and see what you can find."

Outside of music, Alternating Currents also hosts film screenings, comedy performances and other arts events. Almost all of its programming is free to attend.

Espey said that another major announcement for this year is that the film festival will be hosted at The Last Picture House, with more information to be announced later.

"It's a great opportunity to leverage an amazing community asset," she said.

The festival encourages attendees to download the Alternating Currents app, which will be updated as more artists are added to the lineup. Users can follow along with the schedule and create their own custom agenda for the packed weekend.
